                .text-center
                    h2.section-heading.text-uppercase Why Turple?
                    h3.section-subheading.text-muted Turple makes your service agile, scalable and stopless
                .row.text-center
                    .col-md-4
                        img.img-fluid(src='assets/img/why/01-why.png', alt='')

                        h4.my-3 Agile
                        p.text-muted.text-center
                            | The cloud native applications should be agile to respond quickly to whatever happens. In development, deployment and operation application agility is one of the most important matters in cloud native environment.
                    .col-md-4
                        img.img-fluid(src='assets/img/why/02-why.png', alt='')

                        h4.my-3 Scalabe
                        p.text-muted.text-center
                            | One of the important elements required by cloud native environment is scalability. The service should be able to scale in/out by various reasons. If a service application is a Docker container type, Turple can handle all from VM instances to service deployment as needed.
                    .col-md-4
                        img.img-fluid(src='assets/img/why/03-why.png', alt='')

                        h4.my-3 Stopless
                        p.text-muted.text-center
                            | Turple's monitoring system keeps checking the status of VM instances and service applications. Engineers can recognize and resolve issues before the service stops. Even in the worst case Turple's DR(Disaster Recovery) process can resume the service very quickly.

        // portfolio
        section#portfolio.page-section.bg-light
            .container
                .text-center
                    h2.section-heading.text-uppercase Cloud Native Platform
                    h3.section-subheading.text-muted Turple provides everything required by cloud native environment 
                .row
                    .col-lg-4.col-sm-6.mb-4
                        .portfolio-item
                            img.img-fluid(src='assets/img/portfolio/01-thumbnail.png', alt='')
                            .portfolio-caption
                                .portfolio-caption-heading.my-3 High Availability
                                .portfolio-caption-subheading.text-center.text-muted Services of cloud native application must be stopless. The clustering architecture and monitoring system of Turple makes the services fault-tolerant and reliable.
                    .col-lg-4.col-sm-6.mb-4
                        .portfolio-item
                            img.img-fluid(src='assets/img/portfolio/02-thumbnail.png', alt='')
                            .portfolio-caption
                                .portfolio-caption-heading.my-3 Orchestration
                                .portfolio-caption-subheading.text-center.text-muted A cloud native system contains many containers and resource. Turple manages and controls everything with health-checking, service discovery, monitoring, alerting and so on.
                    .col-lg-4.col-sm-6.mb-4
                        .portfolio-item
                            img.img-fluid(src='assets/img/portfolio/03-thumbnail.png', alt='')
                            .portfolio-caption
                                .portfolio-caption-heading.my-3 DevOps
                                .portfolio-caption-subheading.text-center.text-muted DevOps is necessary to make a true cloud native service. When Turple receives a push notification from Github, the updated code is built and the new created container is automatically deployed to designated instances by Turple's CI/CD process.
                    .col-lg-4.col-sm-6.mb-4.mb-lg-0
                        .portfolio-item
                            img.img-fluid(src='assets/img/portfolio/04-thumbnail.png', alt='')
                            .portfolio-caption
                                .portfolio-caption-heading.my-3 Autoscale
                                .portfolio-caption-subheading.text-center.text-muted VM instances are controlled by Turple and can be scaled in/out as required. An engineer can do the job manually by executing simple commands. However the monitoring system can also perform the scaling tasks automatically.
                    .col-lg-4.col-sm-6.mb-4.mb-sm-0
                        .portfolio-item
                            img.img-fluid(src='assets/img/portfolio/05-thumbnail.png', alt='')
                            .portfolio-caption
                                .portfolio-caption-heading.my-3 Monitoring & Logging
                                .portfolio-caption-subheading.text-center.text-muted The monitoring system keeps tracks of all instances and services. The system alerts engineers when detecting abnormal conditions. All logging data are collected by ELK for system analysis.
                    .col-lg-4.col-sm-6
                        .portfolio-item
                            img.img-fluid(src='assets/img/portfolio/06-thumbnail.png', alt='')
                            .portfolio-caption
                                .portfolio-caption-heading.my-3 Heterogeneous
                                .portfolio-caption-subheading.text-center.text-muted The cloud native applications must run in all cloud environments. With Turple the application can be deployed and run in the same way wherever it is. AWS, Azure, OpenStack, Google Cloud, Naver and more are supported by Turple.

